## Section Specifications

## 1) Hero

Goal:
State identity, value proposition, and tone immediately.

Desktop layout:
- 12-column grid
- Left text: 7 columns
- Right visual: 5 columns

Mobile layout:
- Single column
- Headline -> supporting text -> CTA row -> visual

Content constraints:
- Headline max 10 words
- Supporting paragraph max 24 words
- CTA count: 2 primary actions + 1 secondary link max

Suggested CTA set:
- View Work
- GitHub
- LinkedIn

Acceptance criteria:
- First viewport includes identity, value statement, and at least one proof-path CTA.
- No line wraps that create orphan single words in H1 on common mobile widths.

## 2) Expertise

Goal:
Show capability breadth without logo clutter.

Structure:
- 3 capability groups: Front-End Engineering, UI Systems, Modern Web
- Each group has 4-6 concise bullets

Desktop layout:
- 3 cards in a row

Mobile layout:
- stacked cards
- 12-16px inner spacing consistency

Interaction:
- subtle border-lighten on hover/focus
- optional mild elevation (2-4px transform max)

Acceptance criteria:
- Cards remain readable at 320px without text truncation.
- Keyboard focus state visible and high contrast.

## 3) Proof Blocks (Placeholder Mode)

Goal:
Reserve premium case-study space now, using filler content until final projects are ready.

Required block anatomy:
- Project label
- Project name
- Strategic description (1-2 sentences)
- Key capabilities or metrics (3-5 points)
- Stack tags
- Large preview image
- CTA: View Project, View Code

Layout pattern:
- Block 1: text left / preview right
- Block 2: preview left / text right
- Mobile: text first, image second for both

Visual treatment:
- large, cinematic frames (not small cards)
- restrained gradient overlays only if they improve depth hierarchy
- keep decorative layers subtle

Placeholder content to use now:
- Block 1 label: Featured Build
- Block 1 name: Intelligent Interface System (Placeholder)
- Block 1 description: A modular front-end architecture concept focused on clarity, speed, and scalable interaction patterns.
- Block 1 capabilities: semantic search UI, progressive loading, responsive dashboard shell, accessible command actions
- Block 1 stack tags: Next.js, TypeScript, Tailwind, Framer Motion

- Block 2 label: Experimental Build
- Block 2 name: Data-Driven Workspace (Placeholder)
- Block 2 description: A high-density UI exploration for organizing data flows with smooth interaction and clean visual hierarchy.
- Block 2 capabilities: adaptive charts region, filter state orchestration, keyboard-first controls, mobile-first card fallback
- Block 2 stack tags: React, TypeScript, shadcn/ui, Recharts

Placeholder asset rules:
- Use neutral mock screenshots or gradient image placeholders with fixed aspect ratio.
- Keep final dimensions stable to avoid layout shift when real assets are added.
- Keep CTA targets visible, even if links are temporary (#).

Acceptance criteria:
- Each block clearly reads as a future case-study slot, not a tiny project card.
- CTA buttons are visible without hunting.
- Placeholder images are optimized and responsive with no CLS jumps.

## 4) Technical Philosophy

Goal:
Signal engineering maturity and systems thinking.

Content structure:
- 1 headline sentence
- 1 supporting paragraph
- 4-6 principle bullets

Suggested principles:
- clarity over decoration
- performance as UX
- accessibility as baseline quality
- systemized components over ad hoc styling
- maintainability under growth

Acceptance criteria:
- Writing avoids buzzwords and cliches.
- Scannable within one viewport on desktop.

## 5) Contact

Goal:
Minimize conversion friction.

Structure:
- concise prompt line
- GitHub, LinkedIn, optional email
- minimal footer with build stack statement

Acceptance criteria:
- All external links include clear labels and hover/focus states.
- Contact section is reachable in one tap from nav.

